To display a Forsyth–Edwards Notation (FEN) chessboard in LaTeX, you can use the skak package. Here is an example of how to do this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{skak}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\newchessgame[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1]
\chessboard[pgfstyle=border, color=black, markfields={e7,e8}, pgfstyle=straightmove, color=red, markmoves={e7-e8}]
\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\newchessgame[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1]` command sets up the chessboard in FEN notation. The `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1` part of the command is the FEN notation for the starting position of a chess game. The `w KQkq` part of the command specifies that it's white's turn to move and that the king and queen are on their starting squares. The `- 0 1` part of the command specifies that it's move number 1 and that there are no previous moves.

The `\chessboard[pgfstyle=border, color=black, markfields={e7,e8}, pgfstyle=straightmove, color=red, markmoves={e7-e8}]` command then displays the chessboard with a black border around it and marks the squares e7 and e8 in red. The `markfields` option is used to highlight specific squares on the board. The `markmoves` option is used to highlight specific moves on the board. In this case, we are highlighting the move from e7 to e8 with a red straight line.

Note that you need to have both the skak and chessboard packages installed in order for this code to work properly.

